Let everie faithfull body thinke what
is seemelie for them to weare, not so
much by their degree in dignitie, or
condition of riches, as by their religi
on. Excesse in everie thing is discom
mended in Christians. And to what
ende doe wee jagge and gath the gar
mentes that are sowed together to co
ver our bodyes, but that thereby
wee may as it were by a most sende
and ridiculous anatomie, open and
laye foorth to the eyes of all men,
what kinde of people wee are in our
inwarde heartes, jagged (God wot)
and ragged, vaine, light, and nothing
founde? And a linnen or wollen gar
ment doeth as well cover and become
the bodie, as damaskes and velvets,
the cost whereof doeth overlade thy
purse with expenses to buye them,
and misshape thee like an ill favoured
picture, when thou we arest them up
on thee.

Jeremie brin geth in the Lord speaking against the king of Juda, and saying: Woe to him that buildeth his house with unrigh teousnesse, and his parlour with the goods that are wrongfully gotten, which never recompenseth his neigh bours labour, nor payeth him his
hyre: Who sayth to himselfe, I will
builde mee a wide house and gorge
ous parlours: who causeth windowes
to bee hewen therein, and the fee
linges and joystes maketh hee of Ce
dar, and painteth them with Sinoper.
Thinkest thou to reigne nowe, that
thou hast incloased thy selfe with
Cedar? Did not thy father eate and
drinke and prosper well, as long as
he executed justice and equitie?
Let none of us therefore builde sump
tuous houses, by robbing the poore
of their hyre for their lobour. Let e
verie one dwell in a house agreeable to
his profession, degree, and condition.
S. Hierome condemneth sumptuous
cost even in Churches and Tem
ples. Neither doe I see what gorgeous
buildinges bring to a manne, but
mischiefe and miserie. Lord, howe un
willingly doe wee die and depart from
godly dwellinges, whereby we double
the feare of death and terrour of sick
nesse? The Patriarches verily did
dwell in tentes, whereby they wit
nessed that they were pilgrims, and
fought another countrie, the heaven
ly Hierusalem.
Continencie in meate and drinke
is not the loathing of wine and vic
tualles, but the moderate using of
them, to supplie our necessitie, and
not to cloye us with gluttonie.
God in the Scripture doeth con
demne gluttonie, surfettinges, riot
tous afterbanquettes, and dronken
nesse, which hee forbiddeth most of
all. For of dronkennesse doe spring
endlesse miseries, and innumerable
mischiefes, greevous diseases, pover
tie, and pinching beggarie. Salo
mon saith: Who hath woe? who hath
sorrowe? who hath strife? who hath
brawling? who hath woundes with
out a cause? who hath redde eyes?
